The `buildExportData` function attempts to `JSON.parse` all values retrieved from `localStorage`. This is problematic for fields like `DIET_PREFERENCE` and `LANGUAGE` which are stored as plain strings (not JSON-wrapped). If a user has a value that happens to be valid JSON (e.g., a number like "123" or a boolean like "true"), `JSON.parse` will convert it to a number or boolean. This will then cause the `ExportDataSchema` validation to fail during import because it expects a string for these fields. It is safer to explicitly skip parsing for these known plain-string keys.

```typescript
        const isPlainString = key === STORAGE_KEYS.DIET_PREFERENCE || key === STORAGE_KEYS.LANGUAGE;

        try {
            data[key] = isPlainString ? raw : JSON.parse(raw);
        } catch {
            // Fallback for any other unexpectedly non-JSON values
            data[key] = raw;
        }
```","path":"src/utils/dataTransfer.ts","line":75,"author":"gemini-code-assist","created_at":"2026-04-06T16:45:58Z","updated_at":"2026-04-06T16:45:58Z","html_url":"https://github.com/DrDonik/ai-recipe-planner/pull/190#discussion_r3040527854"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

This logic assumes that any value of type `string` should be stored as a plain string in `localStorage`. However, most values in this application are stored as JSON-wrapped strings (e.g., `"\"value\""`). If a future setting is added that stores a string via `useLocalStorage`, this logic will incorrectly store it as a plain string, leading to `JSON.parse` errors when the application attempts to read it back. You should only store as a plain string if the key is specifically known to be a plain-string key.

```typescript
        const isPlainString = key === STORAGE_KEYS.DIET_PREFERENCE || key === STORAGE_KEYS.LANGUAGE;

        if (isPlainString && typeof value === 'string') {
            localStorage.setItem(key, value);
        } else {
            localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));
        }
